To use the WebSocket API for the Text to Speech service in IBM Cloud, you first need to establish a connection to the service using the WebSocket Secure (WSS) protocol. You can do this by calling the /v1/synthesize method, which is available at a specific endpoint that includes your application's location and instance ID.

Once you have established a connection, you can send text and binary messages over the connection to initiate and manage recognition requests. The WebSocket API uses query parameters to authenticate with the service, and message parameters to specify the audio format and any additional parameters for the request.

Here's an example of how you can use the WebSocket API to send a recognition request:

var access\_token = {access\_token};
var wsURI = '{ws\_url}/v1/recognize'
+ '?access\_token=' + access\_token;
var websocket = new WebSocket(wsURI);

websocket.onopen = function(evt) {
var message = {
action: 'start',
content-type: 'audio/flac'
};
websocket.send(JSON.stringify(message));
websocket.send(blob);
websocket.send(JSON.stringify({action: 'stop'}));
}

In this example, we first define the access token and WebSocket URI, and then create a new WebSocket object. We then define an event handler for the WebSocket.onopen event, which is triggered when the connection is established. In this event handler, we send a JSON message to initiate the recognition request, followed by the binary audio data, and then a final JSON message to stop the recognition request.

Note that this is just a basic example, and you will need to define additional event handlers to handle the response from the service, and to manage errors and other scenarios.

For more detailed information about the WebSocket API and its parameters, you can refer to the API & SDK reference at <https://cloud.ibm.com/apidocs/text-to-speech>.

