Yes, IBM Cloudant Query supports sorting the result set in ascending or descending order. If you want to sort the results in reverse order, you can use the "desc" argument in the "sort" field. Here is an example of a query that sorts the results by surname, firstname, and date in descending order:

```json
{
  "selector": {
    "firstname": "Charles",
    "surname": "Dickens"
  },
  "sort": [
    { "firstname": "desc" },
    { "surname": "desc" },
    { "date": "desc" }
  ],
  "limit": 10
}
```
Note that a suitable index must be present that contains the selector fields and the sort fields. Otherwise, IBM Cloudant refuses to execute the query. You can use the [POST /{db}/\_explain](https://cloud.ibm.com/apidocs/cloudant?code=javapostexplain) API endpoint to check which index is being used to service the query. If the index object in the response indicates that "all\_docs" is being used, a full database scan is required to service the query.

